The paper discusses the application and evaluation of the bibliometric method Bradfordizing for information retrieval experiments, which is a topic related to information retrieval (IR) and digital libraries (DL), both of which fall under the category of cs.IR. The paper also mentions the use of controlled experiments and human relevance assessments, which are common in the sub-categories of cs.DL and cs.LG. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of databases from social and political sciences, economics, psychology, and medical science, which could be relevant to the sub-categories of cs.CY and cs.SI.
